{"title_page": "Bohol\u2013Panglao International Airport", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Bohol\u2013Panglao International Airport\n| nativename = {{small|''Paliparang Pandaigdig ng Bohol\u2013Panglao<br>Tugpahanang Pangkalibutanon<br>sa Bohol\u2013Panglao''}}\n| image = [[File:Photo shows the exterior of the Bohol-Panglao International Airport.jpg|270px]]\n| caption = \n| IATA = TAG\n| ICAO = RPSP<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uasc.com/docs/default-source/documents/navigation-database/aptdb_currentcycle_report.pdf?sfvrsn=4c7a945c_86 |date=31 July 2018 |accessdate=4 September 2018 |title=TAWS Airport Database comparison between Cycle 1808 and 1809 |website=Universal Avionics}}</ref>\n| type = Public\n| operator = [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]]\n| city-served = [[Tagbilaran]] and the rest of [[Bohol]]\n| location = Tawala, [[Panglao, Bohol|Panglao]], [[Bohol]]\n| elevation-f = \n| elevation-m = \n| metric-elev = yes\n| coordinates = {{Coord|9|34|N|123|46.5|E|type:airport_region:PH|display=inline,title}}\n| website = \n| pushpin_map = Philippines\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in the Philippines\n| pushpin_label = TAG/RPSP\n| r1-number = 03/21\n| r1-length-f = 8202\n| r1-length-m = 2500\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| metric-rwy = yes\n| stat1-header = \n| stat1-data = \n| stat-year = \n| stat2-header = \n| stat2-data = \n}}\n'''Bohol\u2013Panglao International Airport''' ({{lang-fil|Paliparang Pandaigdig ng Bohol\u2013Panglao}}, {{lang-ceb|Tugpahanang Pangkalibutanon sa Bohol\u2013Panglao}}), also known as '''New Bohol International Airport''' {{Airport codes|TAG|RPSP}}, is a new airport on [[Panglao Island]] in the province of [[Bohol]], Philippines. It replaced [[Tagbilaran Airport]] to support Bohol's increased passenger traffic due to tourism. The airport is dubbed as the first eco-airport in the Philippines and the country\u2019s green gateway.\n\nThe airport is officially classified as an international airport by the [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]].\n\nThe airport serves as the gateway to [[Tagbilaran]] and the rest of mainland Bohol for domestic air travellers. It also is less than an hour's flight from [[Mactan-Cebu International Airport]], which is a gateway to the Central Philippines for international tourists.\n\nThe airport was inaugurated on November 27, 2018 by President [[Rodrigo Duterte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/business/217678-duterte-inaugurates-bohol-panglao-international-airport-november-27-2018|title=Duterte inaugurates Bohol-Panglao International Airport|last=Rey|first=Aika|work=Rappler|date=November 27, 2018|access-date=October 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn September 4, 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/business/09/04/12/neda-board-approves-lrt-airport-projects|title=NEDA board approves Line 2 extension, airport projects|first=by Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN|last=News|publisher=}}</ref> the [[National Economic and Development Authority|NEDA]] Board of the [[Philippines]] approved a resolution giving the green light for the construction of the airport. The proposed airport was to be funded through Official Development Assistance (ODA) instead of the Public-Private Partnership (PPP), an infrastructure-building programme of the government of the Philippines wherein the private sector may participate in any of the schemes authorized by its build-operate-transfer law.\n\nOn March 27, 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jica.go.jp/english/news/press/2012/130327_01.html|title=Signing of Japanese ODA Loan Agreement with the Republic of the Philippines - News & Features - JICA|website=www.jica.go.jp}}</ref> the [[Japan International Cooperation Agency]] signed an agreement with the Republic of the Philippines to build the Bohol\u2013Panglao International Airport at 10.78 billion yen under the project name New Bohol Airport Construction and Sustainable Environment Protection Project. The signing signaled the roll out for the construction of a new airport in the province of Bohol at an island adjacent to [[Tagbilaran Airport]]. Despite the location of the airport, which is just outside of [[Tagbilaran]], it adapted the [[IATA airport code|IATA code]]: TAG from the old airport, which was located in the heart of Tagbilaran.\n\nIn its initial plan, the project was expected to finish in 2016, but the opening was delayed to November 2018.\n\n==Construction==\nInitially, the airport's cost was pegged at \u20b14.8 billion pesos to build<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/p4-8-b-new-panglao-airport-open-to-japanese-contractors/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217071549/http://www.mb.com.ph/p4-8-b-new-panglao-airport-open-to-japanese-contractors/ |archive-date=2013-12-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but was later increased.\n\nOn June 9, 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/business/2014/12/16/1403025/dotc-rolls-out-p116.2-b-bundled-contract-6-airports|title=DOTC rolls out P116.2-B bundled contract for 6 airports|first=Lawrence|last=Agcaoili|publisher=}}</ref> six Japanese firms submitted bids for construction of the proposed airport at a cost of \u20b17.14 billion to be funded from official development assistance (ODA) loan from the [[Japan International Cooperation Agency]]. On December 15, 2014,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/6-japanese-groups-bid-for-bohol-airport-project/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-12-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220160406/http://www.mb.com.ph/6-japanese-groups-bid-for-bohol-airport-project/ |archive-date=2014-12-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the [[Department of Transportation and Communications]] started its search for bidders to bid out for the operations and maintenance (and future extension) of the airport under a concession model.\n\nThe Department of Transport initially planned to award a concession for the operating and maintenance of the airport in combination with two other regional airports. However, in February 2017 the DOTr published an announcement that the project would be tendered as a stand-alone concession, targeting the selection of a contractor in early 2018. Following a change of policy, the concession model was eventually abandoned.\n\n==Structures and Facilities==\n[[File:Panglao Island International Airport aerial view.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view of Bohol-Panglao Airport]]\n\n===Runway===\nThe airport has a {{Convert|2,500|m|ft|sp=us}} asphalt runway that runs in a 03/21 direction. Taxiways E3 and E4 serve as access to the apron from the runway.\n\n===Apron===\n\nThe concrete apron features a total of four (4) parking bays for aircraft as large as the [[Airbus A330]] or a maximum of seven (7) parking bays for narrow bodied aircraft. Also, three (3) passenger jetbridges are installed on the terminal. \n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n[[File:AirAsiaA320atTAG.jpg|thumb|An AirAsia Airbus A320 at the ramp]]\n<br />{{Airport-dest-list\n|[[Air Juan]] | [[Godofredo P. Ramos Airport|Caticlan]], [[Mactan-Cebu International Airport|Cebu]]<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\">{{cite news|last1=Erram|first1=Morexette Marie|date=March 14, 2020|title=Cebu to ban entry of passengers from outside province|url=https://cebudailynews.inquirer.net/294159/cebu-to-ban-entry-of-passengers|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer|Inquirer]]|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>, [[Panan-awan Airport|Maasin]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[AirSWIFT]]|[[El Nido Airport|El Nido]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Cebu Pacific]] | [[Clark International Airport|Clark]], [[Francisco Bangoy International Airport|Davao]] (suspended beginning 19 March 2020 until 2 April 2020)<ref>https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/davao-region-to-suspend-travel-starting-march-19-over-coronavirus-fears</ref> , [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]] (suspended until 14 April 2020)\n<!-- -->\n|[[Cebu Pacific]]<br>operated by [[Cebgo]] | [[Laguindingan Airport|Cagayan de Oro]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Jeju Air]] | [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Philippine Airlines]]<br>operated by [[PAL Express]] | [[Francisco Bangoy International Airport|Davao]] (suspended beginning 19 March 2020 until 2 April 2020)<ref>https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/davao-region-to-suspend-travel-starting-march-19-over-coronavirus-fears</ref>, [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]] (suspended until 14 April 2020)\n<!-- -->\n|[[Philippines AirAsia]] | [[Clark International Airport|Clark]], [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Royhle Air Way]]| '''Charter:''' [[Dumaguete Airport|Dumaguete]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://royhleflight.com/charter/|title=Royhle Air Way Charter \u2013 Royhle Flight Training Academy \u2013 Dumaguete City Philippines|publisher=|access-date=November 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731164826/http://royhleflight.com/charter/|archive-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of airports in the Philippines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://panglaointernationalairport.com/ Official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140806075342/http://ppp.gov.ph/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/New-Bohol-Airport-Investment-Profile.pdf New Bohol Airport Profile at Public-Private Partnership Center]\n\n{{Airports in the Philippines}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bohol-Panglao International Airport}}\n[[Category:Airports in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Bohol]]\n[[Category:Japan International Cooperation Agency]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 2018]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Bohol\u2013Panglao International Airport\n| nativename = {{small|''Paliparang Pandaigdig ng Bohol\u2013Panglao<br>Tugpahanang Pangkalibutanon<br>sa Bohol\u2013Panglao''}}\n| image = [[File:Photo shows the exterior of the Bohol-Panglao International Airport.jpg|270px]]\n| caption = \n| IATA = TAG\n| ICAO = RPSP<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uasc.com/docs/default-source/documents/navigation-database/aptdb_currentcycle_report.pdf?sfvrsn=4c7a945c_86 |date=31 July 2018 |accessdate=4 September 2018 |title=TAWS Airport Database comparison between Cycle 1808 and 1809 |website=Universal Avionics}}</ref>\n| type = Public\n| operator = [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]]\n| city-served = [[Tagbilaran]] and the rest of [[Bohol]]\n| location = Tawala, [[Panglao, Bohol|Panglao]], [[Bohol]]\n| elevation-f = \n| elevation-m = \n| metric-elev = yes\n| coordinates = {{Coord|9|34|N|123|46.5|E|type:airport_region:PH|display=inline,title}}\n| website = \n| pushpin_map = Philippines\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in the Philippines\n| pushpin_label = TAG/RPSP\n| r1-number = 03/21\n| r1-length-f = 8202\n| r1-length-m = 2500\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| metric-rwy = yes\n| stat1-header = \n| stat1-data = \n| stat-year = \n| stat2-header = \n| stat2-data = \n}}\n'''Bohol\u2013Panglao International Airport''' ({{lang-fil|Paliparang Pandaigdig ng Bohol\u2013Panglao}}, {{lang-ceb|Tugpahanang Pangkalibutanon sa Bohol\u2013Panglao}}), also known as '''New Bohol International Airport''' {{Airport codes|TAG|RPSP}}, is a new airport on [[Panglao Island]] in the province of [[Bohol]], Philippines. It replaced [[Tagbilaran Airport]] to support Bohol's increased passenger traffic due to tourism. The airport is dubbed as the first eco-airport in the Philippines and the country\u2019s green gateway.\n\nThe airport is officially classified as an international airport by the [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]].\n\nThe airport serves as the gateway to [[Tagbilaran]] and the rest of mainland Bohol for domestic air travellers. It also is less than an hour's flight from [[Mactan-Cebu International Airport]], which is a gateway to the Central Philippines for international tourists.\n\nThe airport was inaugurated on November 27, 2018 by President [[Rodrigo Duterte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/business/217678-duterte-inaugurates-bohol-panglao-international-airport-november-27-2018|title=Duterte inaugurates Bohol-Panglao International Airport|last=Rey|first=Aika|work=Rappler|date=November 27, 2018|access-date=October 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn September 4, 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/business/09/04/12/neda-board-approves-lrt-airport-projects|title=NEDA board approves Line 2 extension, airport projects|first=by Willard Cheng, ABS-CBN|last=News|publisher=}}</ref> the [[National Economic and Development Authority|NEDA]] Board of the [[Philippines]] approved a resolution giving the green light for the construction of the airport. The proposed airport was to be funded through Official Development Assistance (ODA) instead of the Public-Private Partnership (PPP), an infrastructure-building programme of the government of the Philippines wherein the private sector may participate in any of the schemes authorized by its build-operate-transfer law.\n\nOn March 27, 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jica.go.jp/english/news/press/2012/130327_01.html|title=Signing of Japanese ODA Loan Agreement with the Republic of the Philippines - News & Features - JICA|website=www.jica.go.jp}}</ref> the [[Japan International Cooperation Agency]] signed an agreement with the Republic of the Philippines to build the Bohol\u2013Panglao International Airport at 10.78 billion yen under the project name New Bohol Airport Construction and Sustainable Environment Protection Project. The signing signaled the roll out for the construction of a new airport in the province of Bohol at an island adjacent to [[Tagbilaran Airport]]. Despite the location of the airport, which is just outside of [[Tagbilaran]], it adapted the [[IATA airport code|IATA code]]: TAG from the old airport, which was located in the heart of Tagbilaran.\n\nIn its initial plan, the project was expected to finish in 2016, but the opening was delayed to November 2018.\n\n==Construction==\nInitially, the airport's cost was pegged at \u20b14.8 billion pesos to build<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/p4-8-b-new-panglao-airport-open-to-japanese-contractors/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217071549/http://www.mb.com.ph/p4-8-b-new-panglao-airport-open-to-japanese-contractors/ |archive-date=2013-12-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but was later increased.\n\nOn June 9, 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/business/2014/12/16/1403025/dotc-rolls-out-p116.2-b-bundled-contract-6-airports|title=DOTC rolls out P116.2-B bundled contract for 6 airports|first=Lawrence|last=Agcaoili|publisher=}}</ref> six Japanese firms submitted bids for construction of the proposed airport at a cost of \u20b17.14 billion to be funded from official development assistance (ODA) loan from the [[Japan International Cooperation Agency]]. On December 15, 2014,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/6-japanese-groups-bid-for-bohol-airport-project/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-12-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220160406/http://www.mb.com.ph/6-japanese-groups-bid-for-bohol-airport-project/ |archive-date=2014-12-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the [[Department of Transportation and Communications]] started its search for bidders to bid out for the operations and maintenance (and future extension) of the airport under a concession model.\n\nThe Department of Transport initially planned to award a concession for the operating and maintenance of the airport in combination with two other regional airports. However, in February 2017 the DOTr published an announcement that the project would be tendered as a stand-alone concession, targeting the selection of a contractor in early 2018. Following a change of policy, the concession model was eventually abandoned.\n\n==Structures and Facilities==\n[[File:Panglao Island International Airport aerial view.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view of Bohol-Panglao Airport]]\n\n===Runway===\nThe airport has a {{Convert|2,500|m|ft|sp=us}} asphalt runway that runs in a 03/21 direction. Taxiways E3 and E4 serve as access to the apron from the runway.\n\n===Apron===\n\nThe concrete apron features a total of four (4) parking bays for aircraft as large as the [[Airbus A330]] or a maximum of seven (7) parking bays for narrow bodied aircraft. Also, three (3) passenger jetbridges are installed on the terminal. \n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n[[File:AirAsiaA320atTAG.jpg|thumb|An AirAsia Airbus A320 at the ramp]]\n<br />{{Airport-dest-list\n|[[Air Juan]] | [[Godofredo P. Ramos Airport|Caticlan]], [[Mactan-Cebu International Airport|Cebu]] (Suspended until 16 April 2020)<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\">{{cite news|last1=Erram|first1=Morexette Marie|date=March 14, 2020|title=Cebu to ban entry of passengers from outside province|url=https://cebudailynews.inquirer.net/294159/cebu-to-ban-entry-of-passengers|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer|Inquirer]]|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>, [[Panan-awan Airport|Maasin]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[AirSWIFT]]|[[El Nido Airport|El Nido]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Cebu Pacific]] | [[Clark International Airport|Clark]], [[Francisco Bangoy International Airport|Davao]] (suspended beginning 19 March 2020 until 2 April 2020)<ref>https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/davao-region-to-suspend-travel-starting-march-19-over-coronavirus-fears</ref> , [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]] (suspended until 14 April 2020)\n<!-- -->\n|[[Cebu Pacific]]<br>operated by [[Cebgo]] | [[Laguindingan Airport|Cagayan de Oro]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Jeju Air]] | [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Philippine Airlines]]<br>operated by [[PAL Express]] | [[Francisco Bangoy International Airport|Davao]] (suspended beginning 19 March 2020 until 2 April 2020)<ref>https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/davao-region-to-suspend-travel-starting-march-19-over-coronavirus-fears</ref>, [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]] (suspended until 14 April 2020)\n<!-- -->\n|[[Philippines AirAsia]] | [[Clark International Airport|Clark]], [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]] (suspended until 14 April 2020)\n<!-- -->\n|[[Royhle Air Way]]| '''Charter:''' [[Dumaguete Airport|Dumaguete]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://royhleflight.com/charter/|title=Royhle Air Way Charter \u2013 Royhle Flight Training Academy \u2013 Dumaguete City Philippines|publisher=|access-date=November 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731164826/http://royhleflight.com/charter/|archive-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of airports in the Philippines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://panglaointernationalairport.com/ Official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140806075342/http://ppp.gov.ph/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/New-Bohol-Airport-Investment-Profile.pdf New Bohol Airport Profile at Public-Private Partnership Center]\n\n{{Airports in the Philippines}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bohol-Panglao International Airport}}\n[[Category:Airports in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Bohol]]\n[[Category:Japan International Cooperation Agency]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 2018]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "Meandkancil2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAirlines and destinations:the Suspended Period Already Ends , for Air Juan and Philippine AirAsia (Z2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bohol%E2%80%93Panglao_International_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n| name = Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Riviere_Gouffre.JPG\n| image_caption      = The Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre at [[Baie-Saint-Paul]].\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Canada]]\n| subdivision_type2  = Province\n| subdivision_name2  = [[Quebec]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Capitale-Nationale]]\n| subdivision_type4  = Regional County Municipality\n| subdivision_name4  = [[Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type5  = City\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Baie-Saint-Paul]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|76.1|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=Toponymy>{{cite web|url=http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/toposweb/Fiche.aspx?no_seq=25997|title=Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre, Bank of Quebec place names|website=Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec|accessdate= June 11, 2010}}</ref>\n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= [[Baie-Saint-Paul]]\n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = Lac du C\u0153ur\n| source1_location   = [[Lac-Pikauba, Quebec|Lac-Pikauba]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|47.848478|-70.567861|display=inline}}\n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|823|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = [[St. Lawrence River]]\n| mouth_location     = [[La Malbaie]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|47.75528|69.95361|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|4|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = {{convert|1010|km|mi|2|abbr=on}}\n| tributaries_left   = (from the mouth) Ruisseau du rang Saint-Laurent, ruisseau Gobeil, ruisseau de la Goudronnerie, ruisseau aux rats musqu\u00e9s,  ruisseau du Cap Martin, d\u00e9charge du Lac \u00e0 la Mine, [[rivi\u00e8re \u00e0 La Loutre (Gouffre River tributary)]],  [[rivi\u00e8re de Chicago]], d\u00e9charge du Lac aux Brochets,  ruisseau des Bouliane,  ruisseau des Bergeron, d\u00e9charge du Lac Nice.\n| tributaries_right  = (from the mouth) [[Bras du Nord-Ouest (Gouffre River tributary)|Bras du Nord-Ouest]], [[rivi\u00e8re \u00e0 Renaud]], [[rivi\u00e8re de la Mare]], [[rivi\u00e8re R\u00e9my]], [[Le Gros Bras (Gouffre River tributary)|Le Gros Bras]], ruisseau des Cygnes, ruisseau \u00e0 l'Emp\u00eache, [[rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre Sud-Ouest]], d\u00e9charge du Lac Boudreau,  [[rivi\u00e8re des \u00celets (Gouffre River tributary)]].\n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\nThe '''Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre''' is a tributary of the left bank of the [[Saint-Laurent river]], flowing into the [[Capitale-Nationale]] administrative region, [[Quebec]] ([[Canada]]). This watercourse flows through [[Regional County Municipality]] from:\n* [[Charlevoix-Est]]: unorganized territory of [[Mont-\u00c9lie, Quebec|Mont-\u00c9lie]] (Lacoste township), municipalities of [[Saint-Aim\u00e9-des-Lacs, Quebec|Saint-Aim\u00e9-des-Lacs]] and [[Notre-Dame-des-Monts]];\n* [[Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]]: unorganized territory of [[Lac-Pikauba, Quebec|Lac-Pibauka]] ([[Zec des Martres]]), municipality of [[Saint-Urbain (Quebec)|Saint-Urbain]] and town of [[Baie-Saint-Paul]].\n\nThis hydrographic slope has 185 lakes and 35 tributaries. The [[Zec des Martres]] attracts tens of thousands of visitors each year, particularly because of its mountain trails offering splendid views of the Gouffre River Valley, as well as sport fishing.\n\n== Hydrology ==\nThe Gouffre River has its source at Lac du C\u0153ur (length: {{convert|1.0|km|mi|abbr=on}} altitude: {{convert|823| m}}),<ref name = \"Rivi\u00e8reGouffre\">[http://www.rivieredugouffre.qc.ca / Gouffre River Site]</ref> in the County of Charlevoix West, in the [[Zec des Martres]] which is located east of the [[Grands-Jardins National Park]] and west of [[Hautes-Gorges-de-la-Rivi\u00e8re-Malbaie National Park]]. Lac du Coeur is located at {{convert|4.4|km|mi|abbr=on}} west of Lac des Martres and {{convert|2.0|km|mi|abbr=on}} west of the Charlevoix-Est County boundary.\n\nThe water separation line (altitude: {{convert|910|m}}) between Petit lac Tristan (slope of the [[Malbaie River]]) and the brook of the Mountain (slope of the [[Montmorency River]]) is located {{convert|43.41|km}} west of the northwest shore of the [[St. Lawrence River]] (near the hamlet of Petite-Rivi\u00e8re). From this water separation line, the Malbaie River bypasses the valley of the rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre in a clockwise direction, to flow to [[La Malbaie]] in the [[Saint Lawrence River]]. The hydrographic slope of the Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre stretches inland up to {{convert|47.6|km}} northwest of the mouth of the river.\n\nThe Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre flows towards the Southwest for a total distance of {{convert|76.1|km|mi|abbr=on}} before reaching the [[St. Lawrence River|Saint-Laurent]] at [[Baie-Saint-Paul]]. Its course runs along the western boundary of the municipality of [[Notre-Dame-des-Monts]] and crosses [[Saint-Urbain (Quebec)|Saint-Urbain]]. This river is characterized by its sinuosities and the presence of many rapids.\n\nThe river Gouffre flows on {{convert|76.1|km|mi|abbr=on}} according to the following segments:\n\n'''Upper course of the river''' (segment of {{convert|14.5|km|mi|abbr=on}})\n\nFrom the mouth of the Lac du Coeur, the Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre flows over:\n* {{convert|0.2|km|mi|abbr=on}} northwesterly to the east shore of Lac du Gouffre;\n* {{convert|0.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwesterly across Lac du Gouffre (length: {{convert|0.8|km|mi|abbr=on}}; altitude: {{convert|819|m|ft|abbr=on}});\n* {{convert|1.0|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-east to a small lake (altitude: {{convert|760|m|ft|abbr=on}});\n* {{convert|5.8|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-east to the confluence of a creek (coming from the northeast);\n* {{convert|4.4|km|mi|abbr=on}} south to the confluence of the [[rivi\u00e8re des \u00celets (Gouffre River tributary)|rivi\u00e8re des \u00celets]] (coming from the West);\n* {{convert|0.6|km|mi|abbr=on}} southeasterly to the limit of the Lacoste township;\n* {{convert|2.0|km|mi|abbr=on}} easterly to Lacoste Township, to the western limit of De Sales Township ([[Saint-Aim\u00e9-des-Lacs, Quebec|Saint-Aim\u00e9-des-Lacs]]).\n\n'''Intermediate course of the river''' (segment of {{convert|27.3|km|mi|abbr=on}})\n\nFrom the western limit of De Sales Township, the Gouffre River flows over:\n\n* {{convert|4.3|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the South-East, forming the boundary between the canton of Lacoste and the canton of De Sales, and collecting the waters of the dump of Lake Nice (coming from North-East) ;\n* {{convert|3.6|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the southeast, forming the boundary between [[Saint-Aim\u00e9-des-Lacs, Quebec|Saint-Aim\u00e9-des-Lacs]] and [[Saint-Urbain (Quebec)|Saint-Urbain]], the limit of [[Notre-Dame-des-Monts]];\n* {{convert|5.4|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the southeast, forming the boundary between [[Saint-Urbain (Quebec)|Saint-Urbain]] and [[Notre-Dame-des-Monts]], to Bouliane Creek (from the North);\n* {{convert|2.4|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the South winding to the outlet of the Lac aux Brochets (coming from the East);\n* {{convert|3.9|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwesterly winding to the confluence of the [[Chicago River]] (coming from the Southeast);\n* {{convert|0.3|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwesterly to the [[rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre Sud-Ouest]] (coming from the North);\n* {{convert|1.6|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwesterly to the [[rivi\u00e8re \u00e0 la Loutre (Gouffre River tributary)]] (coming from the South-East);\n* {{convert|3.9|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwesterly to Preveche Creek (from the northwest);\n* {{convert|1.9|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwesterly to the limit of [[Notre-Dame-des-Monts]].\n\n'''Lower course of the river''' (segment of {{convert|34.3|km|mi|abbr=on}})\n\nFrom the limit of [[Notre-Dame-des-Monts]], the river Gouffre flows over:\n\n* {{convert|1.3|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the southwest in [[Saint-Urbain, Quebec|Saint-Urbain]] to the outlet of the Lac \u00e0 la Mine (coming from the South-East);\n* {{convert|2.3|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwesterly to Swan Creek (from the northwest);\n* {{convert|5.4|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwesterly to the river [[Le Gros Bras (Gouffre River tributary)]] (coming from the northwest);\n* {{convert|2.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwesterly winding up to the road bridge of the village of [[Saint-Urbain, Quebec|Saint-Urbain]];\n* {{convert|5.3|km|mi|abbr=on}} southeasterly to the bridge [[Quebec Route 138|route 138]];\n* {{convert|0.2|km|mi|abbr=on}} south to the city limit of [[Baie-Saint-Paul]];\n* {{convert|5.8|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the South winding in [[Baie-Saint-Paul]], until the confluence of the [[R\u00e9my River]] (coming from the West);\n* {{convert|0.2|km|mi|abbr=on}} southeasterly collecting the discharge from the Mares river (coming from the south), to the confluence of the [[ruisseau de la Goudronnerie]] (coming from the Northeast);\n* {{convert|8.1|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the south winding to the confluence of the [[Bras du Nord-Ouest (Gouffre River tributary)]] (coming from the West);\n* {{convert|1.1|km|mi|abbr=on}} southerly forming a northeasterly curve to the road bridge;\n* {{convert|2.1|km|mi|abbr=on}} southeasterly to the confluence of the river.<ref>River segments measured from the Atlas of Canada (published on the Internet), Department of Natural Resources of the Canada.</ref>\n\nThe Gouffre River empties onto the \"Bay Bank\" on the North Shore of the [[St. Lawrence River]] in front of [[\u00cele aux Coudres]]. At the confluence of the river, the strike is long {{convert|1.8|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the southeast at low tide. In addition to the confluence of the Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre, the main rivers flowing over this strike are (from west to east): Verreault Creek, [[Rivi\u00e8re du Moulin (Baie-Saint-Paul)]], Middle Creek, Vases River, Rang Saint-Laurent Creek, Lucien Creek and Bois Blanc Creek.\n\nThe watershed of the Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre covers {{convert|1010|km|2}}. Its main tributaries are the [[Le Gros Bras (Gouffre River tributary)|Le Gros Bras]], [[rivi\u00e8re des Mares]] and the [[rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre Sud-Ouest]]. The total slope of the river is {{convert|686|m|ft|abbr=on}}.\n\n== Toponymy ==\nThe river Gouffre was named by [[Samuel de Champlain]] in 1608.<ref>[http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/CT/toposweb/fiche.aspx?no_seq=25997 Website of the Commission of toponymy of Quebec]</ref> Its name refers to the whirlpool that forms at the foot of Cap aux Corbeaux, downstream from the confluence of the river Gouffre, and which was a source of terror for sailors.\n\nThe toponme \"Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre\" was formalized on December 5, 1968 at the [[Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec]].<ref>[http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/ToposWeb/Fiche.aspx?no_seq=25997 Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec - Bank of Place Names - Toponym: \"Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre\"].</ref>\n\n== Recreational tourism activities ==\nThe Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre is an Atlantic salmon fishing river and a trout.<ref name=\"Rivi\u00e8reGouffre\" />\n\nAt the beginning of the twentieth century, sport fishermen in the Quebec region frequented these waters, which had and still have the reputation of offering large salmon. The population of this species can vary in number significantly from one year to the next. Since 1979, the Association of Conservation of the Valley of the Gouffre (ACVG) manages the salmon fishery. This non-profit organization was formed on March 20, 1979, thanks to the grouping of some forty members. In spring 1979, 100 salmon pits are inventoried in the Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre. Since then, the ACVG has built 65 of these pits. Pedestrian paths run along the river; picnic tables and shelters have been set up. Two bridges span the river allowing fishermen access to all salmon pits.<ref>{{cite web|language=fr|title=Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre SaumonQuebec.com Federation managers of salmon rivers in Quebec (FGRSQ)|url=https://www.saumonquebec.com/dugouffre| website = www.saumonquebec.com| date =| accessdate =2016-07-17}}</ref>\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lac-Pikauba, Quebec|Lac-Pibauka]], a [[unorganized territory|TNO]]\n* [[Mont-\u00c9lie, Quebec|Mont-\u00c9lie]], a TNO\n* [[Saint-Aim\u00e9-des-Lacs, Quebec|Saint-Aim\u00e9-des-Lacs]], a municipality\n* [[Notre-Dame-des-Monts]], a municipality\n* [[Saint-Urbain (Quebec)|Saint-Urbain]], a municipality\n* [[Baie-Saint-Paul]], a city\n* [[Cap-aux-Corbeaux]]\n* [[Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]]\n* [[St. Lawrence River]]\n* [[Grands-Jardins National Park]]\n* [[Zec des Martres]], a harversted controlled zone\n* [[List of rivers of Quebec]]\n\n{{commons category|Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre}}\n{{GeoGroup}}\n== External links ==\n{{Portal bar|Capitale-Nationale|Rivers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gouffre, river du}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Capitale-Nationale]]\n[[Category:Charlevoix Regional County Municipality]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n| name = Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Riviere_Gouffre.JPG\n| image_caption      = The Rivi\u00e8re du Gouffre at [[Baie-Saint-Paul]].\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!-----