|3}}\n|WrittenBy=  Paul W. Cooper\n|DirectedBy= William F. Claxton\n|ProdCode=3013\n|Title= Blizzard\n|ShortSummary= When a serious snowstorm threatens to strand the children in the schoolhouse on the last day before Christmas vacation, Miss Beadle dismisses the children early. Unfortunately, many are unable to get home and the men of Walnut Grove must organize a search party.  But for one particular family, it will not be a merry Christmas.\n|LineColor=7D32B3\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=58\n|EpisodeNumber2=12\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|1|10}}\n|WrittenBy= Paul W. Cooper\n|DirectedBy= William F. Claxton\n|ProdCode=3010\n|Title= I'll Ride the Wind\n|ShortSummary= John is offered a scholarship in Chicago that will allow him to live his dream of becoming a writer. This causes Mary and John much heartache, as they must decide whether to remain together or risk a separation for the sake of John's career.\n|LineColor=7D32B3\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=59\n|EpisodeNumber2=13\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|1|17}}\n|WrittenBy=  John Hawkins\n|DirectedBy= Victor French\n|ProdCode=3015\n|Title= Quarantine\n|ShortSummary= Mr. Edwards and Doc Baker provide help to a nearby town during a mountain fever epidemic. When Mr. Edwards returns, Walnut Grove is placed under quarantine and Alicia, Mr. Edward's daughter, becomes ill with the disease. Laura, unaware of the danger, visits the Edwards' home and helps nurse her friend back to health.  \n|LineColor=7D32B3\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=60\n|EpisodeNumber2=14\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|1|24}}\n|WrittenBy= Dale Eunson\n|DirectedBy= William F. Claxton\n|ProdCode=3014\n|Title= Little Women\n|ShortSummary= While Laura and Mary prepare a play for school with Ginny Clark, they learn that Ginny wants her mother, who is a single parent, to date again. Ginny decides to use the play to help her mom gain the confidence necessary to meet new people.\n|LineColor=7D32B3\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n