ith a single apple to split. \n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=194\n|EpisodeNumber2=12\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|1|3}}\n|WrittenBy=Michael Landon\n|DirectedBy=Michael Rhodes\n|ProdCode=8463\n|Title= Marvin's Garden\n|ShortSummary= An aging doctor ([[Ralph Bellamy]]) is losing his sight and knows he will soon have to retire. Meanwhile, Jenny nearly drowns while looking for her locket in the lake. Her brain is partly damaged and she is unable to walk, talk and use her hands. Dr. Marvin convinces Laura to let Jenny help him with his garden to rehabilitate. She turns out to be his last patient.\n\n''Note'': The main theme to this episode's original score would later serve as the theme music to Michael Landon's next series, ''[[Highway To Heaven]]''.\n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=195\n|EpisodeNumber2=13\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|1|10}}\n|WrittenBy=E. F. Wallengren\n|DirectedBy=Victor French\n|ProdCode=8464\n|Title= Sins of the Fathers\n|ShortSummary= Sarah Carter's imposing father visits Walnut Grove, demanding they move back to New York City. Sarah will not listen and she is finally allowed to stay with her family in Walnut Grove.\n\n''Note'': Victor French and Dean Butler do not appear in this episode.\n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=196\n|EpisodeNumber2=14\n|WrittenBy=Michael Landon\n|DirectedBy=Victor French\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|1|17}}\n|ProdCode=8455\n|Title= The Older Brothers\n|ShortSummary= Mr. Edwards, and later, Almanzo and John, become mixed up with the criminal activities of a bumbling gang of outlaws.\n\n''Notes:'' An episode of ''[[Bonanza]]'', titled \"The Younger Brothers' Younger Brother\", had a story with a similar theme to this episode. Both episodes were written by Michael Landon.\n\n''Guest stars'': [[Geoffrey Lewis (actor)|Geoffrey Lewis]], [[Robert Donner]], [[Timothy Scott (actor died 1995)|Timothy Scott]] \n''Note'': Melissa Gilbert, Katherine MacGregor and Richard Bull do not appear in this episode. \n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=197\n|EpisodeNumber2=15\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|1|24}}\n|WrittenBy=Don Balluck\n|DirectedBy=Maury Dexter\n|ProdCode=8465\n|Title= Once Upon a Time\n|ShortSummary= At Almanzo's urging, Laura enters a writing contest and produces a novel about the Ingalls family, which Almanzo and Jenny love. After travelling with Jenny to Minneapolis, Laura learns that she has won the contest and she is offered the opportunity to have her novel published. She reluctantly agrees to changes which the publishers want to make, but Jenny convinces Laura that the new version is not as good as her original and should not be published.\n\n''Note'': As the episode ends, Michael Landon narrates a [[flashforward]] (taken from \"The Little House Years\"), in which his daughter Shawna Landon is the little girl running into the public library to read [[Laura Ingalls Wilder]]'s third book, ''[[Little House on the Prairie (novel)|Little House on the Prairie]]''. In real life, Laura did not start writing the 'Little House' books until she was in her fifties, encouraged to do so by her daughter [[Rose Wilder Lane|Rose]], who was by then herself a successful journalist and author. \n\n''Note'': Victor French, Richard Bull and Katherine MacGregor do not appear in this episode.\n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=198/199\n|EpisodeNumber2=16/17\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|2|7}}\n|WrittenBy=Michael Landon\n|DirectedBy=Michael Landon\n|ProdCode=8467/033210\n|Title= Home Again: Episodes 1 & 2\n|ShortSummary= Charles and Albert return to Walnut Grove after Albert has repeated run-ins with the law for curfew violations and theft. It is soon discovered that Albert is hooked on morphine, which increasingly causes his behavior to be violent and eventually leads Charles to take drastic measures to help his son withdraw from the drug.  At the end, it is stated that Albert returned to Walnut Grove years later as \"Doctor Albert Ingalls\u201d.  Since the later follow-up movie \u201cLook Back To Yesterday\u201d never shows Albert dying of his illness on-screen, it can be implied that Albert\u2019s return as a doctor happened between the events of the former story and the finale, \u201cThe Last Farewell\u201d, with his death (if it ever happened at all) to follow.\n\n''Notes'': Originally aired as a two-hour episode. In both [[television syndication|syndication]] and the Lionsgate/NBC DVD, it is shown as a two-part episode. Final series appearances of Michael Landon and [[Matthew Laborteaux]], who both return in the post-series movies.\n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=200\n|EpisodeNumber2=18\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|2|14}}\n|WrittenBy=Don Balluck\n|DirectedBy=Victor French\n|ProdCode=8466\n|Title= A Child with No Name\n|ShortSummary= \"In the late summer of 1889\", Almanzo and Laura's newborn son dies overnight from [[Sudden Infant Death Syndrome|no obvious cause]] at only a week old. Without any real reason, Laura blames Doc Baker for the baby's death and his reputation and business is badly damaged, so he decides to leave Walnut Grove. Then Rose becomes sick with [[smallpox]] and, against Laura's wishes, Almanzo calls in Doc Baker, who has to stay with them in quarantine. After Rose recovers, Laura acknowledges that she had been wrong and that Doc Baker is a good doctor, and she persuades him to stay.\n\n''Note'': This is the final appearance of [[Ketty Lester]] as Hester-Sue Terhune.\n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=201\n|EpisodeNumber2=19\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|2|21}}\n|WrittenBy=Duke Sandefur\n|DirectedBy=Maury Dexter\n|ProdCode=8469\n|Title= The Last Summer\n|ShortSummary= Jason begins doing odd jobs for an aging woman, Ruthy Leland ([[Vera Miles]]). Sarah becomes jealous over the blossoming friendship, until Ruthy reveals her that she is dying.  Jason makes plenty of happy memories with his friend before her death.\n\n''Note:''  Victor French and Dean Butler do not appear in this episode.\n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=202\n|EpisodeNumber2=20\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|3|7}}\n|WrittenBy=Michael Landon\n|DirectedBy=Michael Landon\n|ProdCode=8470\n|Title= For the Love of Blanche\n|ShortSummary= Mr. Edwards promises to care for a dying traveler's \"baby,\" only to discover it to be an orangutan named Blanche, which makes quick friends with everyone except Nancy, who tries to swat the animal, only for it to fight back. Mrs. Oleson wants Blanche killed, but Mr. Edwards devises a plan to trick them into thinking Blanche is dead. Mr. Edwards decides that Blanche needs to live in a zoo. Later, Blanche saves Rose from a potentially deadly house fire that Jenny puts out, and when Jenny tells the story at school, Nancy finds out that Blanche is still alive. Mrs. Oleson demands that the sheriff make sure Blanche is dead this time, but the ape hides in a tree until the arrival of the zookeeper, who convinces the sheriff and Mrs. Oleson to let Blanche live.\n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=203\n|EpisodeNumber2=21\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|3|14}}\n|WrittenBy=Chris Abbott\n|DirectedBy=Victor French\n|ProdCode=8471\n|Title= May I Have This Dance?\n|ShortSummary= Willie graduates and his mother expects him to go on to college, but Willie has fallen in love with his girlfriend Rachel Brown, and wants to get married and take over the running of the family's restaurant.  Mrs. Oleson opposes his plans and cruelly insults Rachel, and when Willie stands up to his mother and defends Rachel against her, she vows not to show up at the wedding. In the event, she does go, but theatrically dressed in black funeral clothes. Nels later reminds Harriet that his mother similarly opposed their marriage, and he says he has never regretted it. Meanwhile, Mrs. Flannery, a childless elderly friend of Laura's, passes away after gifting her big house to Laura and Almanzo, who set about turning it into a boardinghouse, and Willie and Rachel move in as their first boarders.\n\n''Note'': This is the first appearance of Rachel Brown-Oleson ([[Sherri Stoner]]), who also appears in the series finale and the three subsequent TV movies.\n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber=204\n|EpisodeNumber2=22\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|3|21}}\n|WrittenBy=Don Balluck\n|DirectedBy=Michael Landon\n|ProdCode=8472\n|Title= Hello and Goodbye\n|ShortSummary= Matthew's ([[Jonathan Hall Kovacs]]) natural father arrives in Walnut Grove, wanting to reclaim custody after years of searching for him. Initially, Matthew is angry that his parents abandoned him as a baby, but, after learning why they did it and receiving a gift of his late mother's Bible, Mr. Edwards helps him to decide to leave town to live with his father. A devastated Mr. Edwards decides he will move into Laura's new boarding house, where a multi-talented English writer named Sherwood Montague (Robert Casper Lilley) has also taken up residence.\n\n''Note'': At the conclusion of the 1982\u201383 season, NBC decided to cancel the series. Despite still ranking in the top 30 programs, ''Little House'' had two consecutive years of declining ratings, and Landon had not imagined the series lasting long enough for Laura to become an independent, married woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/02/06/arts/prairie-set-is-dynamited-for-finale.html|title='PRAIRIE' SET IS DYNAMITED FOR FINALE|first=Stephen|last=Farber|website=Nytimes.com|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> To wrap up the storylines, three TV movies were aired in the following television season. This is the last appearance of Harriet Oleson ([[Katherine MacGregor]]), who does not appear in the post-series movies. On the other hand, this marks the first appearance of Sherwood Montague, who appears in all three post-series movies. Hello and Goodbye was the last episode for \"Do You Love Me?\" by [[David Rose (songwriter)|David Rose]]. It was also the last episode for the logo of [[Worldvision Enterprises]] containing the original title music by [[Frank Becker (composer)|Frank Becker]].\n|LineColor=F3CC06\n}}\n}}\n\n== Post-series movie specials (1983\u201384) ==\n{{Episode table\n|background=#1c1c1c\n|title=21\n|writer=19\n|director=15\n|airdate=15\n|prodcode=7\n|episodes=\n\n{{Episode list\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1983|12|12}}\n|WrittenBy=Vince R. Gutierrez\n|DirectedBy=[[Victor French]]\n|ProdCode=8486\n|RTitle= ''Little House: Look Back to Yesterday''\n|ShortSummary= In Burr Oak, Iowa, Charles gets a promotion as a Purchasing Agent, and he takes Albert with him on a buying trip to Minnesota. En route, they stop at the University of Minnesota where Albert plans on pursuing his medical endeavours, then they reunite with family and old friends in Walnut Grove. Albert finds romance with a girl called Michele Pierson, and Charles encourages the local farmers to start a cooperative to enable them to compete with the big farms.  However, Albert starts suffering from serious nosebleeds and exhaustion and is diagnosed with [[leukemia]]. Ultimately, he chooses to go back to Walnut Grove, where he spends his time making special memories and receives the offer of a four-year scholarship from the university he had planned on attending. Finally, Albert, Laura and Michele join Miss Plum and the local school children in their annual climb to 'the keepsake tree' at the top of Harper's Bluff, where they join hands and raise them in a celebratory salute.\n\n*This is the final appearance of Matthew Labyorteaux as Albert. Originally aired as a 95-minute movie (excluding commercials), when offered in [[television syndication|syndication]], it is shown either in two parts or in its entirety. \n*In an interview years later, producer Kent McCray confirmed the intention was always that Albert died of his illness, although it was never depicted on-screen and contradicted the epilogue of the episode \u201cHome Again\u201d which acknowledges that Albert returned to Walnut Grove years later as a doctor. This in turn contradicts the \u201cFinal Farewell\u201d episode. \n|LineColor=1c1c1c\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1984|12|17}}\n|WrittenBy=[[Chris Abbott|Chris Abbott-Fish]]\n|DirectedBy=Victor French\n|ProdCode=0407\n|RTitle= ''Little House: Bless All the Dear Children''\n|ShortSummary= Just before Christmas in 1896, Laura and Almanzo and Mr. Edwards are shopping for gifts in Mankato when Rose is kidnapped by a grief-stricken mother, prompting a desperate search. A young orphan boy, Sam, stows away in their wagon and becomes a key player in the search and its happy outcome. Meanwhile, in Walnut Grove, Nels tries to get Nancy to contribute to the Olesons' Christmas but later regrets it; Jason tries to earn money for gifts with a Christmas tree delivery service which nobody wants; and Mr. Montague tries to avoid all the seasonal customs but ends up saving the Carters' Christmas.\n*Originally aired as a 95-minute movie (excluding commercials), when offered in syndication, it is shown either in two parts or in its entirety. The movie was originally intended to air in December 1983 but was not aired until December 1984, 10 months after the official series finale ''Little House: The Last Farewell''\n*In its original NBC telecast, Bless All the Dear Children ranked 18th of 65 programs in the weekly Nielsen ratings, with an 18.2 rating and 27% share of the audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/84-OCR/BC-1984-12-31-OCR-Page-0110.pdf#search=%22paper%20dolls%22|format=PDF|title=USFL scrambling for radio and TV coverage|website=Americanradiohistory.com|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n|LineColor=1c1c1c\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1984|2|10}}\n|WrittenBy=Michael Landon\n|DirectedBy=Michael Landon\n|ProdCode=0400\n|RTitle= ''Little House: The Last Farewell''\n|ShortSummary= Charles and Caroline visit Walnut Grove and are pleased to be able to stay in the 'Little House' when John and Sarah Carter go out of town. Then the townspeople learn that a land development tycoon, Nathan Lassiter ([[James Karen]]), has acquired title to all the land in Hero Township, which they had believed to be homesteading land. Having failed to defeat his claim on legal grounds and even with guns against an army cavalry unit, the townspeople are inspired by Laura to vent their anger at what they see as an injustice, and they decide upon a drastic plan of action. When Lassiter arrives to claim the town, he finds all the town buildings dynamited, and the townsfolk leave to start new lives elsewhere, as many of them have done before. He is forced to relent, however, when he is told that the leaders and businessmen of other nearby towns, having heard what happened in Walnut Grove, announce they will do the same thing. As Lassiter walks off in defeat, Reverend Alden loudly proclaims that Walnut Grove did not die in vain, prompting a huge celebration.\n*Originally aired as a 95-minute movie (excluding commercials), when offered in syndication, it is shown either in two parts or in its entirety. \n*In its original NBC telecast, The Last Farewell finished 9th of 59 programs in the weekly Nielsen ratings with a 22.0 rating and 32% share of the audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/84-OCR/BC-1984-02-20-OCR-Page-0082.pdf#search=%22little%20house%20last%20farewell%22|format=PDF|title=Country Radio reprises in Nashville|website=Americanradiohistory.com|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n|LineColor=1c1c1c\n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Epguides|LittleHouseonthePrairie|Little House on the Prairie}}\n* {{tv.com show|little-house-on-the-prairie|Little House on the Prairie}}\n* {{IMDb title|0071007|Little House on the Prairie}}\n\n{{Little House}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Little House On The Prairie Episodes}}\n[[Category:Lists of American drama television series episodes]]\n[[Category:Lists of American Western television series episodes]]\n[[Category:Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|*]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Little_House_on_the_Prairie_episodes"}
{"title_page": "Matthew Formston", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson|\n| name = Matthew Formston\n| image =File:XXXX15 - Matt Formston - 3b - 2016 Team processing.jpg\n| caption = 2016 Australian Paralympic Team Portrait\n| headercolor = green\n| textcolor = yellow\n| nationality = {{AUS}}\n| club = [[Central Coast (cycling team)|Central Coast]]\n| nickname = Formo\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|07|21|df=yes}} <ref name=one>{{cite web|title=Rider Profiles|url=http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|publisher=Cycling Australia|accessdate=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Sydney]] <ref name=one/>\n| <!-- Sport -->\n| disability = [[Visual Impairment]]\n| coach = \n| height =\n| weight =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[para-cycling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{AUS}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold |Aguascalientes 2014 | Tandem B Pursuit}}\n{{MedalSilver |Appledoon 2015 | Tandem B Pursuit}}\n}}\n\n'''Matthew Formston''' (born 21 July 1978) is a legally blind Australian Professional Para Surfer and former professional Para Cyclist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/matt-formston/|title=Matt Formston - Paralympics Australia|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Formston won gold and silver medals at the 2014 and 2015 [[UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships]] and represented Australia with pilot [[Nick Yallouris]], at the [[2016 Rio Paralympics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/matt-formston/|title=Matt Formston - Paralympics Australia|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Formston also holds three consecutive world titles for [[Surfing]] (2017, 2018 and 2020) at the ISA Para Surfing World Championships <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.surfingaustralia.com/news/team-australias-bloom-and-formston-claim-gold-medals-at-the-2018-stance-isa-world-adaptive-surfing-championship-presented-by-the-city-of-san-diego|title=Team Australia\u2019s Bloom and Formston Claim Gold Medals at the 2018 Stance ISA World Adaptive Surfing Championship presented by the City of San Diego|website=www.surfingaustralia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> (VI Division) as the 2016 to 2019 Australian Champion, 2018 and 2019 US Adaptive Open (Gold) and 2017, 2018, 2019 Dukes Ocean Fest Hawaii Gold medalist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.surfingaustralia.com/news/stewart-and-formston-win-gold-at-dukes-oceanfest|title=Stewart And Formston Win Gold At Duke's OceanFest|website=www.surfingaustralia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nFormston was born on 21 July 1978 in Sydney, New South Wales. At the age of five, Formston was diagnosed with [[Macular dystrophy, vitelliform|Macular Dystrophy]] eventually reducing his sight to 0% central vision and 5% [[peripheral vision]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mattformston.com/about/|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is legally blind. With a Diploma of Health Science <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|title=Cycling Australia > High Performance > Rider Profiles > Male > Matthew Formston|date=2015-09-23|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and extensive business and competitive sport experience, Matt holds a national executive role as Head of Sustainability and [[Corporate social responsibility|Corporate Social Responsibility]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.optus.com.au/about/careers/inside-optus/inspiration/from-blind-cycling-to-surfing-meet-matt-formston|title=From blind cycling to surfing, meet Matt Formston|website=www.optus.com.au|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. He is also a sought after [[Keynote Speaker|keynote speaker]], [[Business coaching|business coach]] and offers strategic training workshops to promote high performing teams and resilient leadership. Matt Formston and his wife Rebecca have three children and live on the [[Central Coast (New South Wales)|Central Coast of New South Wales]].\n\n==Career==\n\n==== Competitive Sports ====\nFormston's cycling career began in 2009 while on a charity ride for the Macular Disease Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greatlakesadvocate.com.au/story/4123482/matt-hops-on-his-bike-for-rios-gamesphotos/|title=Matt hops on his bike for Rio's games{{!}}photos|last=Duncan|first=Jeanene|date=2016-08-26|website=Great Lakes Advocate|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The ride took Formston from [[Sydney]] to [[Melbourne]] and he successfully completed it on a single bike. In 2012, Formston was named the Central Coast Cyclist of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|title=Cycling Australia > High Performance > Rider Profiles > Male > Matthew Formston|date=2015-09-23|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Formston originally rode competitively with [[Phillip Thuaux]] in 2010 before pairing with Mick Curran in 2012 as a tandem partner and the pair were known as OzTandem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.betaview.com.au/blog/oz-tandemthe-most-inspirational-cycling-team-youll-ever-meet/|title=Oz Tandem:The Most Inspirational Cycling Team You\u2019ll Ever Meet|date=2013-03-25|website=BetaView|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Curran, a fully sighted competitor, held the role of pilot for the duo. They went on to win gold in both track and road cycling on most continents around the globe and amassed 12 Australian National Titles between 2012 and 2016. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blindsportsnsw.com.au/news/champion-surfer-and-paralympian-matt-formston-appointed/|title=News - Blind Sports NSW - revolutioniseSPORT|website=www.blindsportsnsw.com.au|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the pair won gold in the Tandem Road Race at the UCI Para-cycling Road World Cup in Canada.  In 2014, Formston and Curran set a new world record in the Tandem Pursuit event clocking a time of 4:11.213.  In the same year, they took home the gold medal at the 2014 UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships in [[Aguascalientes|Aguascalientes, Mexico]]. Formston and Curran competed in the 2015 UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships in [[Apeldoorn]], [[Netherlands]] and finished second in the Tandem Pursuit.\n\nFormston and Curran's bond went beyond the tandem bike with the pair starting their own business known as Champion Vision.\n\nAt the 2016 Rio Paralympics, Formston's new cycling pilot was [[Nick Yallouris]] from [[Chittaway Point, New South Wales]] eventually announcing his retirement from competitive cycling the same year.\n\nIn 2016, Formston was awarded the [[New South Wales Institute of Sport]] Scholarship to continue his pursuit of competitive cycling and surfing. \n\nIn 2017, Formston appeared alongside [[Ron McCallum]] on the Season 2 premiere episode of ABC's ''[[You Can't Ask That]]'' entitled \"Blind People\".\n\nAs a professional surfer, Formston is the current Para Surfing World Champion, winning the 2017, 2018 and 2020 ISA World Para Surfing Championships (VI Division).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.surfingaustralia.com/news/isaresults|title=Aussie Pair Formston & Bloom Win Gold At 2020 AmpSurf ISA World Para Surfing Championship|website=www.surfingaustralia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He won the 2016, 2017, 2018 and 2019 \u00a0Australian Championships as well as the 2018 and 2020 US Adaptive Open (Gold).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://usopenadaptivesurfingchampionships.com/results/|title=Results \u2013 US Open Adaptive Surfing Championships.s|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> In addition, Formston achieved the 2017, 2018 and 2019 Dukes Ocean Fest Hawaii (Gold) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.surfingaustralia.com/news/stewart-and-formston-win-gold-at-dukes-oceanfest|title=Stewart And Formston Win Gold At Duke's OceanFest|website=www.surfingaustralia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and took home the 2018 Huntington Adaptive Pro (Gold). \n\nFormston has a range of surfing sponsors including Firewire, Slater Designs and [[Billabong (clothing)|Billabong]].\n\n==== Executive and Professional Coaching ====\nMatt Formston is a sought after [[Keynote Speaker|keynote speaker]] in [[strategic leadership]], offering executive [[business coaching]] and professional workshop facilitation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mattformston.com/services|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As a Gold medalist, world title holder and [[Paralympian]], Formston uses his extensive experience in [[sport psychology]], visualisation, goal setting as well as corporate experience as a successful business executive to deliver tactics to turn challenges into strengths. \n\nFormston has delivered individual and group coaching to a range of corporate executives across companies such as [[Hewlett-Packard|Hewlett Packard]], [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]], [[PepsiCo|Pepsi Co]], [[Optus]], Lend Lease, [[Institution of Civil Engineers]], [[Deloitte]], Orthoptics Australia, [[Vision Australia]] and [[Macquarie University]].\n\nAs Chair of the Macquarie Business Park Partnership, Formston has led corporate executives to deliver a modern approach to overcoming community disadvantage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.linkedin.com/in/matt-formston-04430983|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n*2012 - Central Coast Cyclist of the Year <ref name=\"one\">{{cite web|title=Rider Profiles|url=http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|publisher=Cycling Australia|accessdate=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/matt-formston/ Australian Paralympic Committee profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston Cycling Australia profile]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6u6yBBY3B3Q We Believe - Matt Formston and Nick Yallouris]\n*[http://mattformston.com/about/ Personal Website]\n\n{{2016 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|Australia|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Formston, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australia at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic cyclists of Australia]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic cyclists with a vision impairment]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Australia]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australian male cyclists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson|\n| name = Matthew Formston\n| image =File:XXXX15 - Matt Formston - 3b - 2016 Team processing.jpg\n| caption = 2016 Australian Paralympic Team Portrait\n| headercolor = green\n| textcolor = yellow\n| nationality = {{AUS}}\n| club = [[Central Coast (cycling team)|Central Coast]]\n| nickname = Formo\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|07|21|df=yes}} <ref name=one>{{cite web|title=Rider Profiles|url=http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|publisher=Cycling Australia|accessdate=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Sydney]] <ref name=one/>\n| <!-- Sport -->\n| disability = [[Visual Impairment]]\n| coach = \n| height =\n| weight =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[para-cycling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{AUS}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold |Aguascalientes 2014 | Tandem B Pursuit}}\n{{MedalSilver |Appledoon 2015 | Tandem B Pursuit}}\n}}\n\n'''Matthew Formston''' (born 21 July 1978) is a legally blind<ref name=\"two\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oztandem.com|title=OzTandem|publisher=OzTandem|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811065102/http://www.oztandem.com/|archive-date=11 August 2015|accessdate=20 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Australian Professional Para Surfer and former professional Para Cyclist. Formston won gold and silver medals at the 2014 and 2015 [[UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships]] and represented Australia with pilot [[Nick Yallouris]], at the [[2016 Rio Paralympics]].<sup>[3]</sup> Formston also holds three consecutive world titles for [[Surfing]] (2017, 2018 and 2020) at the ISA Para Surfing World Championships (VI Division) as the 2016 to 2019 Australian Champion, 2018 and 2019 US Adaptive Open (Gold) and 2017, 2018, 2019 Dukes Ocean Fest Hawaii Gold medallist.\n\n==Personal==\nFormston was born on 21 July 1978 in Sydney, New South Wales.<sup>[1]</sup> At the age of five, Formston was diagnosed with [[Macular dystrophy, vitelliform|Macular Dystrophy]] eventually reducing his sight to 0% central vision and 5% [[peripheral vision]].<sup>[4]</sup> He is legally blind.<sup>[2]</sup> With a Diploma of Health Science and extensive business and competitive sport experience, Matt holds a national executive role as Head of Sustainability and [[Corporate social responsibility|Corporate Social Responsibility]]. He is also a sought after [[Keynote Speaker|keynote speaker]], [[Business coaching|business coach]] and offers strategic training workshops to promote high performing teams and resilient leadership. <sup>[1]</sup> Matt Formston and his wife Rebecca have three children and live on the [[Central Coast (New South Wales)|Central Coast of New South Wales]].\n\n==Career==\n\n==== Competitive Sports ====\nFormston's cycling career began in 2009 while on a charity ride for the Macular Disease Foundation. The ride took Formston from [[Sydney]] to [[Melbourne]] and he successfully completed it on a single bike. In 2012, Formston was named the Central Coast Cyclist of the Year. Formston originally rode competitively with [[Phillip Thuaux]] in 2010 before pairing with Mick Curran in 2012 as a tandem partner and the pair were known as OzTandem.<sup>[2]</sup> Curran, a fully sighted competitor, held the role of pilot for the duo. They went on to win gold in both track and road cycling on most continents around the globe and amassed 12 Australian National Titles between 2012 and 2016.\n\nIn 2013, the pair won gold in the Tandem Road Race at the UCI Para-cycling Road World Cup in Canada. <sup>[1]</sup> In 2014, Formston and Curran set a new world record in the Tandem Pursuit event clocking a time of 4:11.213. <sup>[6]</sup> In the same year, they took home the gold medal at the 2014 UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships in [[Aguascalientes|Aguascalientes, Mexico]].<sup>[6]</sup> Formston and Curran competed in the 2015 UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships in [[Apeldoorn]], [[Netherlands]] and finished second in the Tandem Pursuit.\n\nFormston and Curran's bond went beyond the tandem bike with the pair starting their own business known as Champion Vision.\n\nAt the 2016 Rio Paralympics, Formston's new cycling pilot was [[Nick Yallouris]] from [[Chittaway Point, New South Wales]]<sup>[9]</sup> \u00a0eventually announcing his retirement from competitive cycling the same year.\n\nIn 2016, Formston was awarded the [[New South Wales Institute of Sport]] Scholarship to continue his pursuit of competitive cycling and surfing.<sup>[11]</sup>\n\nIn 2017, Formston appeared alongside [[Ron McCallum]] on the Season 2 premiere episode of ABC's ''[[You Can't Ask That]]'' entitled \"Blind People\".<sup>[12]</sup>\n\nAs a professional surfer, Formston is the current Para Surfing World Champion, winning the 2017, 2018 and 2020 ISA World Para Surfing Championships (VI Division). He won the 2016, 2017, 2018 and 2019 \u00a0Australian Championships as well as the 2018 and 2020 US Adaptive Open (Gold). In addition, Formston achieved the 2017, 2018 and 2019 Dukes Ocean Fest Hawaii (Gold) and took home the 2018 Huntington Adaptive Pro (Gold). \n\nFormston has a range of surfing sponsors including Firewire, Slater Designs and [[Billabong (clothing)|Billabong]].\n\n==== Executive and Professional Coaching ====\nMatt Formston is a sought after [[Keynote Speaker|keynote speaker]] in [[strategic leadership]], offering executive [[business coaching]] and professional workshop facilitation. As a Gold medallist, world title holder and [[Paralympian]], Formston uses his extensive experience in [[sport psychology]], visualisation, goal setting as well as corporate experience as a successful business executive to deliver tactics to turn challenges into strengths. \n\nFormston has delivered individual and group coaching to a range of corporate executives across companies such as [[Hewlett-Packard|Hewlett Packard]], [[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]], [[PepsiCo|Pepsi Co]], [[Optus]], Lend Lease, [[Institution of Civil Engineers]], [[Deloitte]], Orthoptics Australia, [[Vision Australia]] and [[Macquarie University]].\n\nAs Chair of the Macquarie Business Park Partnership, Formston has led corporate executives to deliver a modern approach to overcoming community disadvantage.\n\n==Recognition==\n*2012 - Central Coast Cyclist of the Year <ref name=\"one\">{{cite web|title=Rider Profiles|url=http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|publisher=Cycling Australia|accessdate=20 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.paralympic.org.au/athlete/matt-formston/ Australian Paralympic Committee profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212331/http://www.cycling.org.au/High-Performance/Rider-Profiles/Male/ProfileId/49/Matthew-Formston Cycling Australia profile]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6u6yBBY3B3Q We Believe - Matt Formston and Nick Yallouris]\n*[http://mattformston.com/about/ Personal Website]\n\n{{2016 Australian Paralympic Team}}\n{{Portal bar|Australia|Biography|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Formston, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australia at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic cyclists of Australia]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic cyclists with a vision impairment]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Australia]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australian male cyclists]]\n", "name_user": "EmmaWiki01", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding references to Updated text.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matthew_Formston"}
